      <outline text="BASIC #linear #basic #wfe-ignore-item ">
        <outline text="Assets #CI7100 #CI7130_Intro #slide #CI7160-intro #basic ">
          <outline text="In order to better understand security attacks, we have to define what we want to protect" />
          <outline text="This is called an asset" />
          <outline text="We categorise assets in the following way:">
            <outline text="System (logical)" />
            <outline text="Hardware" />
            <outline text="Software" />
            <outline text="Data" />
            <outline text="People" />
          </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Assets #slide #CI7100 #CI7130_Intro #CI6240_SM-1 #basic ">
          <outline text="!&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.dropbox.com/s/wy569h036gsfa0v/assets.png?dl=1&quot;&gt;assets.png&lt;/a&gt; #wfe-style:normal " />
        </outline>
        <outline text="Mini-Exercise: Assets #slide #CI7100 #CI7130_Intro #basic ">
          <outline text="Look around you. There are many assets of the Kingston University system present. List some asset items, with at least one in each category. " />
          <outline text="Which of them do you consider being critical assets -- these would be assets of particular value or importance for your student experience." />
        </outline>
        <outline text="The Goals of Computer Security #slide #CI7100 #CI7160-intro #CI7130_Intro #basic ">
          <outline text="We will define as the main goals (or requirements) of Computer Security (“CIA”):">
            <outline text="Confidentiality" />
            <outline text="Integrity" />
            <outline text="Availability" />
          </outline>
          <outline text="This terminology is adopted by academia and industry" />
          <outline text="Note: cannot “guarantee” absolute security" />
        </outline>
        <outline text="Confidentiality #slide #CI7100 #CI7160-intro #CI7130_Intro #basic ">
          <outline text="Definition: computer related assets must be accessed only by authorised parties" />
          <outline text="Synonyms: secrecy, privacy" />
          <outline text="Example: you need to prevent hackers from accessing personal data in your social network account" />
          <outline text="There may be different levels of confidentiality for different users" />
        </outline>
        <outline text="Integrity #slide #CI7100 #CI7160-intro #CI7130_Intro #basic ">
          <outline text="Data Integrity:">
            <outline text="Data has not been modified by unauthorised parties" />
            <outline text="Example: file transfer, email, computer viruses" />
          </outline>
          <outline text="Origin Integrity (Authentication):">
            <outline text="We have proof about origin of a message" />
            <outline text="Example: IP address of the machine the e-mail was sent from" />
          </outline>
          <outline text="Non-repudiation:">
            <outline text="Sender (or recipient) of a message cannot deny having been involved in message transfer" />
            <outline text="This is more complex (usually involves 3 parties)" />
          </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Availability #slide #CI7100 #CI7160-intro #CI7130_Intro #basic ">
          <outline text="Definition: assets are accessible to authorised parties at appropriate times" />
          <outline text="In other words: legitimate access should always be possible" />
          <outline text="Example: a website should be available 24/7." />
          <outline text="Different availability levels" />
        </outline>
        <outline text="Confidentiality, Integrity and Availability #slide #CI7100 #CI7160-intro #CI7130_Intro #basic ">
          <outline text="!&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.dropbox.com/s/i12op0g3xmcby27/CIA.png?dl=1&quot;&gt;CIA.png&lt;/a&gt; #eyo-style:Normal " />
        </outline>
        <outline text="Threats, Vulnerabilities, Attacks and Risks #slide #CI7100 #CI7160-intro #CI7130_Intro #basic ">
          <outline text="&lt;i&gt;Threat&lt;/i&gt;: set of circumstances with potential to exploit vulnerability and create a risk of harm" />
          <outline text="&lt;i&gt;Vulnerability&lt;/i&gt;: potentially exploitable weakness of an asset" />
          <outline text="&lt;i&gt;Attack&lt;/i&gt;: realisation of a threat (&quot;threat event&quot;)" />
          <outline text="&lt;i&gt;Risk&lt;/i&gt;: occurs if “matching” threat and vulnerability exist" />
        </outline>
        <outline text="Controls #slide #CI7100 #CI7160-intro #CI7130_Intro #basic ">
          <outline text="A control is used for protection." />
          <outline text="It could be for example an">
            <outline text="action," />
            <outline text="procedure," />
            <outline text="device," />
            <outline text="technique." />
          </outline>
          <outline text="It either eliminates the threat and/or closes the vulnerability." />
          <outline text="Controls need to be effective." />
        </outline>
        <outline text="#todo Basic Security Methodology #slide #CI6240_SM-1 #CI7100 #CI7160_D1 #CI7130_Intro #basic ">
          <outline text="The basic methodology in computer security is:">
            <outline text="We detect uncovered vulnerabilities in our system" />
            <outline text="We think about potential threats to our system" />
            <outline text="Finally, we consider available controls (countermeasures)" />
          </outline>
          <outline text="Impossible to guarantee security, can only minimise risk" />
          <outline text="Need for periodic review" />
        </outline>
        <outline text="Generic Security Methodology #slide #CI7160-intro ">
          <outline text="For each critical asset do:">
            <outline text="Identify potential threats" />
            <outline text="Detect uncovered vulnerabilities" />
            <outline text="Assess potential risks" />
            <outline text="Design controls (countermeasures)" />
          </outline>
          <outline text="Constant re-evaluation is necessary">
            <outline text="Anticipate potential new threats (for example: http://www.cert.org)" />
            <outline text="Identifies areas where more work is needed" />
            <outline text="Review existing controls" />
            <outline text="Monitor technological progress" />
          </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Mini-Exercise: Security Goals #slide:mini #CI7100 #CI7130_Intro #basic ">
          <outline text="Read the story about the recent security incident at &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theregister.co.uk/security/&quot;&gt;The Register&lt;/a&gt;." />
          <outline text="Analyse the story more in-depth (you may have to research older, related articles) and identify which of the main security goals were violated, and of which (critical) assets." />
        </outline>
      </outline>
      <outline text="Advanced section #h " />
      <outline text="ADVANCED #wfe-ignore-item ">
        <outline text="VULNERABILITIES&lt;b&gt; &lt;/b&gt;#wfe-ignore-item ">
          <outline text="More About Vulnerabilities #slide #CI7130_Intro #basic ">
            <outline text="Depending on the vulnerable asset type, we can identify:">
              <outline text="Hardware Vulnerabilities" />
              <outline text="Data Vulnerabilities" />
              <outline text="Software Vulnerabilities" />
              <outline text="People Vulnerabilities" />
            </outline>
          </outline>
          <outline text="Hardware Vulnerabilities #slide #CI7130_Intro ">
            <outline text="Physical Vulnerabilities">
              <outline text="Hardware is composed of physical objects -- it is simple to add, change, destroy or remove parts. " />
              <outline text="This means that computer devices might be prone to a physical attack. " />
              <outline text="Computers have been stolen, kicked, punched, burnt, frozen, shot at.. the &lt;a href=&quot;&lt;a href=&quot;https://youtu.be/algWjS2yiyE&quot;&gt;proof&lt;/a&gt;!&quot;&gt;https://youtu.be/algWjS2yiyE) !&lt;/a&gt;" />
              <outline text="Before the University tightened its physical controls, every semester at least one projector used to be stolen!" />
            </outline>
            <outline text="Microprocessor Design Flaws">
              <outline text="Recent huge issue: flaws in Intel/ARM chip design (&quot;Meltdown&quot; and &quot;Spectre&quot;)" />
              <outline text="This is actually a combination of hardware and software vulnerabilities " />
            </outline>
          </outline>
          <outline text="Data Vulnerabilities #slide #CI7130_Intro ">
            <outline text="Enormous amounts of data around (big data), connected and exposed to the Internet, and stored on corporate clouds. " />
            <outline text="Data can be human-readable (text) or in binary format. " />
            <outline text="Need to think of data at rest, and in transit (computation/memory, hard disk, network, brain). " />
            <outline text="Data attacks are more widespread than software attacks. ">
              <outline text="Unprotected data is &quot;easy&quot; to read and intrinsically vulnerable to all threat outcomes (interception, interruption, modification)." />
              <outline text="Furthermore, it can be easily duplicated. " />
            </outline>
          </outline>
          <outline text="Software Vulnerabilities #slide #CI7130_Intro ">
            <outline text="Software is also data, so all data vulnerabilities apply" />
            <outline text="Weaknesses can appear during different stages of software development and deployment life cycle:">
              <outline text="Source Code">
                <outline text="Coding Flaws: mistakes in the design of source code, weak cryptographic implementations (ignoring standards)." />
              </outline>
              <outline text="Compiled (Binary) Code">
                <outline text="Inherently vulnerable to malicious exploits (buffer overflow, SQL injection). " />
                <outline text="Expanded attack surface due to frequent use of common libraries. " />
              </outline>
              <outline text="Deployed Application">
                <outline text="Misconfiguration: weaknesses such as security patches out of date, weak security settings (e.g., default passwords). " />
              </outline>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Software vulnerabilities are indexed in the CVE catalogue on &lt;a href=&quot;http://cve.org&quot;&gt;cve.org&lt;/a&gt;. " />
          </outline>
          <outline text="People Vulnerabilities #slide #CI7130_Intro ">
            <outline text="People are often the weakest link." />
            <outline text="Typical exploit: phishing/spam emails." />
            <outline text="Effectiveness is often underestimated." />
            <outline text="This is particularly problematic if the targeted people are key individuals within an IT system, such as system administrators or lecturers." />
            <outline text="Vulnerabilities:">
              <outline text="Lack of security awareness -- people tend to use computers irresponsibly." />
              <outline text="Lack of skills, training, and expertise -- not having the technical know-how in security." />
              <outline text="Personality Weaknesses">
                <outline text="Laziness and forgetfulness -- writing down or reusing passwords, forgetting to make backups, etc." />
                <outline text="Naivety -- if this persists despite training, people are an ideal target for social engineering." />
              </outline>
            </outline>
          </outline>
          <outline text="OLD #wfe-ignore-outline ">
            <outline text="Software Vulnerabilities #slide #CI7130_Intro ">
              <outline text="Weaknesses can appear during different stages of software development and deployment life cycle:">
